 1996.Kline translated more of Brodsky’s poems than any other single person, with the exception of Brodsky himself. The Bryn Mawr philosophy professor and Slavic scholar was a modest and retiring man, but on occasion he could be as forthright and adamant as Brodsky himself. “Akhmatova discovered Brodsky for Russia, but I discovered him for the West,” he claimed.Kline’s interviews with author Cynthia L. Haven before his death in 2015 include a description of his first encounter with Brodsky, the KGB interrogations triggered by their friendship, Brodsky's emigration, and the camaraderie and conflict over translation. When Kline called Brodsky in London to congratulate him for the Nobel, the grateful poet responded, “And congratulations to you, too, George!”  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aRussian poetryy20th centuryxTranslations into English. 0aTranslatorszUnited StatesvInterviews. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Literary.2bisacsh  aA Halt in the Desert.  aBryn Mawr.  aJoseph Brodsky.  aKGB.  aLeningrad.  aOstanovka v pustyne.  aRussian literature.  aSelected Poems.  aSlavic Languages.  aSoviet Union.  aWorld War II.  aartists.  abiography.  acensorship.  acollaboration.  aculture.  aemigration.  ahistory.  ainterviews.  ameter.  aphilosophy.  apoetry.  apublishing.  arhyme.  ascholarship.  atranslation.  awriting.1 aPolukhina, Valentina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAcademic Studies Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311068820708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2020 Part 2z978311069629508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK 